This paper deals with the computation of betweenness centrality in large complex networks, which is a problem that falls under the scope of several computer science sub-disciplines. The most likely category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), as the paper focuses on network analysis and centrality measures. The use of arrays, lists, and stacks also suggests a possible connection to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also mentions the size of a subset of edges in the graph, which could be related to cs.SD (Software Engineering) or cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Finally, the incremental nature of the algorithm could be relevant to cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture).
